KNN¶

Optimizing K¶

We calculate the mean square error in different optmization techniques to get to the best K possible

In [13]:
# Optimize with regular average
parameters = {"n_neighbors": range(1, 25)}
gridsearch = GridSearchCV(KNeighborsRegressor(), parameters)
gridsearch.fit(A_train, b_train)
Out[13]:
GridSearchCV(estimator=KNeighborsRegressor(),
             param_grid={'n_neighbors': range(1, 25)})
In [14]:
# Determine test error after optimizing with regular average
test_preds_grid = gridsearch.predict(A_test)
test_mse = mean_squared_error(b_test, test_preds_grid)
test_rmse = sqrt(test_mse)
test_rmse
Out[14]:
0.18525876294673596
In [15]:
# Optimize with weighted average
parameters = {
     "n_neighbors": range(1, 25),
     "weights": ["uniform", "distance"],
}
gridsearch = GridSearchCV(KNeighborsRegressor(), parameters)
gridsearch.fit(A_train, b_train)
Out[15]:

             param_grid={'n_neighbors': range(1, 25),
                         'weights': ['uniform', 'distance']})

Selecting the best max for classifying using cross validation¶

In [41]:
depth = []
for i in range(1,12):
    clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=i,criterion = 'entropy',random_state=3)
    # Perform 10-fold cross validation 
    scores = cross_val_score(estimator=clf, X=A_train, y=b_train, cv=10)
    depth.append(scores.mean())
print(depth)
best_depth = max(depth)
print("Best depth score is : " , best_depth)
best_depth = depth.index(best_depth)
print("Best depth is : " , best_depth+1)
